<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-03T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-03T19:00:00-05:00" n="522" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d522">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">684A.85/8–150: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Legation in Jordan</gloss>
                                </hi><note n="1" xml:id="d522fn1">This telegram was repeated to Arab
                                    capitals, London, Tel Aviv, and Jerusalem (for Mr.
                                    Palmer).</note>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-03T20:00:00-04:00">August
                                        3, 1950—8 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>22. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 28, Aug 1. Dept believes
                                such proposals as Israel–Jordan high level military talks or
                                inclusion political reps on <gloss target="#t_MAC1">MAC</gloss> do
                                not conflict with <gloss target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss> efforts
                                achieve overall settlement. On contrary Dept believes that they are
                                complementary. Dept fears present border frictions may prejudice
                                chances <gloss target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss> success in bringing
                                parties together <pb facs="0987" n="965" xml:id="pg_965"/> and
                                believes implementation these proposals will tend create atmosphere
                                more conducive successful negotiations. Dept agrees, however, that
                                appearance pressing proposals upon parties might have unfavorable
                                results, and believes gradual development should be permitted.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>